                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1390" notAfter="1410" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                            <p>The manuscript is written in <origDate>Iceland</origDate>. <name
                                    type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kristian Kålund</name> dated it to
                                the fourteenth century (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">KKKat</ref>
                                </bibl>) whereas <name type="person" key="OscJoh001">Oscar Albert
                                    Johnsen</name> and <name type="person" key="JonHel003">Jón
                                    Helgason</name> later dated it more precisely to <origDate
                                    notBefore="1390" notAfter="1410" cert="high"
                                    evidence="conjecture">c. 1400</origDate> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="OlHJH">Johnsen &amp; Jón
                                        Helgason 1941</ref><biblScope unit="page"
                                    >959</biblScope></bibl>).</p>
                        </origin>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>On the old cover of the manuscript <name type="person"
                                    key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> tells that he found the 2
                                leaves in <date when="1713">1713</date> in the back of Throndheim's
                                chapter revenues of the Trondheim chapter. The cadastre was written
                                in <name type="place">Trondheim</name> in <date>1618</date> and was
                                probably also bound there; later it belonged to <name type="person"
                                    key="JenRos001">Jens Ronsenkrantz</name>, titular Councillor of
                                State, and <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name>
                                bought it after his death in 1702: <q xml:lang="is">Þesse 2.
                                        in<expan>n</expan>lỏgdu blỏd fan<expan>n</expan> eg 1713.
                                        in<expan>n</expan>ani hryggnum ä einne Iardabok yfir
                                    Throndhiems Capitels indkomster gi<expan>or</expan>de 1618.
                                    hveria iardabok eg eignast hafde 1702 efter Etats Raad Jens
                                    Rosencrantz. en<expan>n</expan> e<expan>ck</expan>j athugad hana
                                    so grant fyrr en<expan>n</expan> nu. bokin<expan>n</expan> var
                                        in<expan>n</expan>saumud, og þesse 2 blỏd lỏgd
                                        in<expan>n</expan>ani pergam<expan>en</expan>ted til
                                    styrktar vid hryggen<expan>n</expan>. Bokin<expan>n</expan> er
                                    samantekin i Nidarose, og so (öefad) blỏdin þar
                                        in<expan>n</expan>ani hana lỏgd</q>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
